				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">S.&#038;P. Lowers Puerto Rico Debt to Junk Status</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Mary Williams Walsh			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-04T21:24:51+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 4, 2014 4:24 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 4, 2014 4:24 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/05/business/DEBT/DEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/05/business/DEBT/DEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/05/business/DEBT/DEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002688653" width="592" height="395" alt="The ratings agency said the islandâs debt load, by a conservative measurement, was $10,635 per capita, more than 10 times the median level for the states."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The ratings agency said the islandâs debt load, by a conservative measurement, was $10,635 per capita, more than 10 times the median level for the states.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Christopher Gregory/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/02/04/s-p-lowers-puerto-rico-debt-to-junk-status/" data-title="S.&#038;P. Lowers Puerto Rico Debt to Junk Status" data-description="The move intensified a cash squeeze for the commonwealth, whose financial condition is of outsize importance to the rest of the United States because its debt is widely held by individual investors through mutual funds.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><br />
<span id="t20h35m" class="update">Updated, 8:35 p.m. | </span><a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Standard &amp; Poor's." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/standard_and_poors/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Standard &amp; Poorâs</a> downgraded the debt of Puerto Rico to junk status on Tuesday, intensifying a cash squeeze for the commonwealth, whose financial condition is of outsize importance to the rest of the United States because its debt is widely held by individual investors through <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about mutual funds and exchange-traded funds." href="//topics.nytimes.com/your-money/investments/mutual-funds-and-etfs/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier">mutual funds</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">S.&amp;P., which lowered its rating to BB+ from BBB-, said it had decided that Puerto Rico was no longer qualified as investment grade because its government was losing its ability to raise cash through the Government Development Bank. It said it did not expect the cash squeeze to ease soon and was keeping all of Puerto Ricoâs debt on negative watch, which means more downgrades could follow.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The implications of slipping into junk territory are greater than a one-notch downgrade might suggest. A good portion of Puerto Ricoâs debt was issued with promises to make cash payments if it fell below investment grade, and ready cash is precisely what Puerto Rico lacks. S.&amp;P. estimated that the downgrade would initiate cash calls totaling $940 million, including the acceleration of debt service and the posting of additional collateral on interest-rate swaps.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some of those commitments call for Puerto Rico to produce the cash within 30 days.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe understand that the G.D.B. is currently negotiating to have certain debt holders waive acceleration provisions,â S.&amp;P. said, referring to the Government Development Bank, which orchestrates the islandâs many borrowings, among other duties. S.&amp;P. said the development bank was also âarranging for new multiyear external bank credit lines that could mitigate near-term liquidity risks.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Some institutional holders of Puerto Ricoâs debt have rules saying they cannot hold junk-rated debt, although those rules typically kick in after two such downgrades by the top rating agencies. That left market participants watching for the next downgrade; <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Moody's Investors Service." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/moodys_corporation/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Moodyâs Investors Service</a> and <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about Fitch Ratings" href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/news/business/companies/fitch_ratings_inc/index.html?inline=nyt-org">Fitch Ratings</a> both rate Puerto Ricoâs debt a single notch above junk.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI think youâd be hard-pressed to find any financial professional who did not think Puerto Rico did not deserve an investment grade rating,â said Matt Fabian, a managing director at Municipal Market Advisors. âYou have to expect more downgrades.â He said the mere fact that S.&amp;P. had taken the step would reduce market confidence, making downgrades by the other firms more likely.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Puerto Rico had been planning to bring $1 billion to $2 billion <a title="Related article." href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/01/21/2-billion-deal-in-works-for-puerto-rico/?_php=true&amp;_type=blogs&amp;_r=0">of new debt</a> to market this month or next. The downgrade and cash calls seemed likely to complicate that borrowing.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Puerto Rican treasury secretary, Melba Acosta Febo, and the chairman of the Government Development Bank, David H. Chafey Jr., issued a joint statement on Tuesday confirming that they were having discussions with unidentified parties about how to address immediate cash needs.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe are confident that we have the liquidity on hand to satisfy all liquidity needs until the end of the fiscal year, including any cash needs resulting from todayâs decision,â the two officials said.</p>
<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/05/business/JP-DEBT/JP-DEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/05/business/JP-DEBT/JP-DEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/05/business/JP-DEBT/JP-DEBT-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002688661" width="592" height="310" alt="Vacant buildings along the coast of San Juan, Puerto Rico. The commonwealth has roughly $70 billion of debt outstanding."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="310"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Vacant buildings along the coast of San Juan, Puerto Rico. The commonwealth has roughly $70 billion of debt outstanding.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Christopher Gregory/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">They added that they were disappointed about the downgrade, but they said they remained committed to the fiscal and economic development plans the commonwealth has announced over the last year, in response to <a title="Related article." href="//www.nytimes.com/2012/11/27/business/puerto-rico-races-to-rescue-its-pension-fund.html">growing doubts</a> about its ability to carry so much debt. Puerto Rico has roughly $70 billion of debt outstanding and is â despite a population of fewer than four million people â the third-largest issuer of <a class="tickerized" title="More articles about municipal bonds." href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/m/municipal_bonds/index.html?inline=nyt-classifier">municipal bonds</a> in the United States, after California and New York. Its debt has long been popular and easy for underwriters to sell because, thanks to Puerto Ricoâs status, it offers tax-exempt interest to investors in all 50 states.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">S.&amp;P. cited a smaller level of debt, about $38 billion, because it was counting only debt repaid by tax revenue. Even using that narrower measure, it said, the islandâs debt load was $10,635 per capita, more than 10 times the median level for the states. Puerto Rico also has a shrinking population, so the per capita burden is rising. In addition, its economy has been suffering through a long and deep recession, and in recent years a large amount of the debt was issued to balance the budget.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Top elected officials in Puerto Rico have said that prospective investors on the mainland fail to appreciate their plans and the steps they have taken, some of which have drawn fire from the islandâs residents. They have been developing a new security for bond issues in the future, trying to bring underground economic activity to the surface, and selling public assets to private investors, among other activities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The changes have been politically difficult. An attempt in December to overhaul the Puerto Rican pension fund for teachers led to a strike, lawsuits and a court order halting the changes until legal questions could be ironed out. An overhaul of the pension fund for other public workers went forward earlier in the year, but only after the fund ran through almost all its money, bottoming out at an all-but-unheard-of funded ratio of 4 percent. Underfunded pensions are a concern to bond buyers because it is not clear who will be paid first if the government doesnât have enough cash to pay both.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Michael Corkery contributed reporting.</em></p>
